b:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 mb-6 not-prose","children":["$","ul",null,{"className":"space-y-2.5 border-l-4 border-yellow-400/50 pl-4","children":[["$","li","0",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Toxic protein duo triggers brain cell destruction in mice"}]]}],["$","li","1",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"New compound breaks pairing, slows disease progression"}]]}],["$","li","2",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Human trials remain speculative—demo vs. deployment gap"}]]}]]}]}]
c:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 article-prose max-w-none","children":[["$","p",null,{"children":["Scientists have found a new villain in Alzheimer’s research: a toxic pairing of two proteins acting as a ‘death switch’ for brain cells. ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2024/05/240515123417.htm","children":"The study"}],", published via ",["$","em",null,{"children":"ScienceDaily Health"}],", confirms that breaking this duo with a novel compound slowed disease progression in mice—reducing amyloid buildup and protecting neurons. The results are real, but the leap to human applications is where the hype begins.\nThe compound’s mechanism is the actual news here. Unlike broad-spectrum amyloid-targeting drugs (see: ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.statnews.com/2024/04/10/eli-lilly-alzheimers-drug-donemab-fda-delay/","children":"Eli Lilly’s recent setbacks"}],"), this approach pinpoints a specific protein interaction. That precision could sidestep the collateral damage of earlier treatments. Early signals suggest it’s a more elegant solution—",["$","em",null,{"children":"if"}]," it translates beyond rodents.\nYet the press cycle is already framing this as a ‘breakthrough.’ ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.alzheimersresearchuk.org/","children":"Alzheimer’s Research UK"}]," notes that mouse models notoriously overpromise; human trials, if they happen, will take years. The real signal isn’t the discovery—it’s the pattern: another lab success that may or may not survive the valley of death between bench and bedside."]}],"\n",["$","div",null,{"className":"not-prose my-8 pt-6 border-t border-white/10","children":[null,["$","div",null,{"className":"glass-card overflow-hidden mb-4 !hover:transform-none","children":["$","img",null,{"src":"/images/articles/alzheimers-death-switch-the-mouse-study-hype-filte/subtitle.jpg","alt":"The gap between lab success and clinical reality is wider than the press release admits","className":"w-full h-auto max-h-[400px] object-cover"}]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-text-secondary italic text-lg leading-relaxed font-medium","children":"The gap between lab success and clinical reality is wider than the press release admits"}]]}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":["The industry map here is predictable. Big Pharma will scramble to license or replicate the compound, while biotech startups will pitch ‘death switch’ platforms to VCs. The ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://github.com/topics/alzheimers-research","children":"GitHub activity"}]," around protein-interaction modeling has spiked, but it’s still niche—no open-source frenzy yet. Developers are watching, not betting.\nWhat’s missing from the narrative? The deployment reality. Even if the compound works in humans, Alzheimer’s is a multi-factorial disease. Amyloid is just one piece; tau tangles, inflammation, and vascular damage play roles too. A single ‘switch’ fix is unlikely. The ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.nia.nih.gov/alzheimers","children":"NIH’s latest framework"}]," emphasizes combination therapies—this study doesn’t invalidate that.\nThe competitive advantage goes to whoever can turn this into a ",["$","em",null,{"children":"stackable"}]," treatment. Right now, it’s a compelling demo with a long road ahead. The community’s cautious optimism is telling: after decades of failed trials, no one’s celebrating yet."]}]]}]
